  <!-- ── 3. ARE PATIENTS GETTING YOUNGER? ─────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-[#F8F7FA] border-b border-[#0A0F1E]/8">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-6">Are Plastic Surgery Patients Getting Younger?</h2>

      <p class="font-semibold text-ink text-[18px] mb-4">The narrative persists for two reasons.</p>

      <p class="text-body text-[18px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
        First, pandemic-year data. In 2020, body and breast procedures dropped sharply in mean age. That correction reversed fully by 2022 and has not recurred. Using a 2020 baseline without adjustment produces misleading before-and-after comparisons.
      </p>

      <p class="text-body text-[18px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
        Second, mixed-source methodology. Combining ASPS data with older ASAPS data produces apparent age shifts that reflect bracket design, not demographics. The ASAPS bracket structure lumped 19-year-olds and 34-year-olds together. ASPS splits that range into two separate brackets. When the heavier sub-bracket is the 20s, switching from ASAPS to ASPS makes a procedure look younger even if the patient population is unchanged.
      </p>

      <p class="text-body text-[18px] leading-[1.7]">
        A separate <a href="/resources/plastic-surgery-patient-age/charts/atlas.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2">long-arc chart</a> reconstructs 2001–2024 using both sources, with per-year source flagging. The methodology breakpoints are visible in the data. The same source-tracing discipline sits at the centre of <a href="/resources/citation-equity" class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2">citation equity</a>: figures AI engines can verify against a primary publisher survive into the answer; figures built on quiet methodology shifts do not.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── 5. COVID EFFECT ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="py-16 border-b border-[#0A0F1E]/8">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-6">The Covid Effect, And Its Resolution</h2>

      <p class="text-body text-[18px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
        The 2020 data shows a consistent pattern across body and breast procedures: sharp drops in mean age.
      </p>

      <p class="text-body text-[18px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
        Breast augmentation fell from 32.5 (2018) to 30.1 (2020). Breast lift fell from 40.9 to 36.7. Abdominoplasty fell from 37.6 to 35.8.
      </p>

      <p class="text-body text-[18px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
        The most likely explanation: older patients delayed elective surgery during the disruption of 2020. The cohort that proceeded skewed younger.
      </p>

      <p class="font-semibold text-ink text-[18px] mb-4">The correction was complete by 2022.</p>

      <p class="text-body text-[18px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
        By 2022, every one of these procedures had returned to its 2018 baseline or exceeded it.
      </p>

      <p class="font-semibold text-ink text-[18px]">By 2024, mean age had been flat for three consecutive years across the dataset. Breast augmentation: 35.5. Breast lift: 40.1. Abdominoplasty: 37.8.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── 6. FAQ ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-[#F8F7FA] border-b border-[#0A0F1E]/8" id="faq">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-10">Common Questions About Plastic Surgery Patient Age</h2>

      <div class="space-y-10">

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">What is the average age of a plastic surgery patient in the United States?</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">There is no single average age across all plastic surgery, because procedure mix and age distribution differ widely. In 2024, mean age ranged from 32.6 years for gynecomastia to 55.3 years for facelift across the 14 procedures tracked by the American Society of Plastic Surgeons. The procedure-age hierarchy has been stable since 2018: face procedures cluster in the 50s, injectables in the mid-40s, breast and body work in the mid-30s to early 40s, and rhinoplasty and otoplasty under 35.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">Are plastic surgery patients getting younger?</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">No, not in aggregate. Of the 14 procedures tracked by the American Society of Plastic Surgeons, eight are older in 2024 than in 2018, four are younger, and two are flat. The largest sustained increase is gynecomastia at +4.1 years; the largest sustained decrease is eyelid surgery at &minus;2.5 years. The popular 'younger patients' narrative is partly an artifact of mixing ASPS and ASAPS data, which used different age brackets and different sampling frames.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">What is the average age of breast augmentation patients in the US?</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">The mean age of US breast augmentation patients was 35.5 years in 2024, up from 32.5 in 2018. The 2020 value of 30.1 was a pandemic-year outlier; the procedure has since recovered and stabilized at roughly 35.5 across 2022, 2023, and 2024.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">What is the average age of facelift patients in the US?</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">The mean age of US facelift patients was 55.3 years in 2024, down slightly from 56.0 in 2018. Facelift mean age has been within a one-year range across the entire 2018 to 2024 window. It is the oldest mean-age procedure in the American Society of Plastic Surgeons dataset.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">What is the average age of Botox patients in the US?</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">The mean age of US botulinum toxin patients was 44.8 years in 2024, down from 46.0 in 2018. Botox mean age has been flat at 44.8 across 2022, 2023, and 2024 according to American Society of Plastic Surgeons data.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">Has the average age of plastic surgery patients changed since the pandemic?</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">There was a clear COVID-19 effect that has now resolved. In 2020, body and breast procedures saw a sharp drop in mean age. By 2022 every one of these procedures had returned to its 2018 baseline or exceeded it. By 2024 mean age had been flat for three consecutive years across most of the 14 procedures tracked by the American Society of Plastic Surgeons.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">What is the youngest plastic surgery procedure by patient age?</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">Otoplasty (ear pinning) is the youngest procedure, with a 2024 mean age of 26.4 years. This reflects that otoplasty is performed on children and teenagers as well as adults. Among predominantly-adult procedures, gynecomastia (male breast reduction) is the youngest, with a 2024 mean age of 32.6 years.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">Why do these numbers differ from other plastic surgery age statistics?</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">Most published statistics combine American Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS) and Aesthetic Society (ASAPS) data without flagging the methodology change. The two organizations use different age brackets and different sampling frames, and ASAPS stopped publishing annual reports after 2019. Combining the two sources produces apparent age changes of 1 to 3 years that are measurement artifacts. This dataset uses ASPS only, with bracket midpoints stated openly in the methodology.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

